05075nam a22004575i 9780814795149DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20002000nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147951497 a10.18574/nyu/9780814795149.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)679311  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0100002bisacsh1 aWilson, John K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHow the Left Can Win Arguments and Influence People :bA Tactical Manual for Pragmatic Progressives /cJohn K. Wilson. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2000] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical America ;v5800tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction: The Progressive Majority: How the Left Got Left Behind -- tChapter 1 The Death of Socialism -- tChapter 2 The Vast Right-Wing Conspiracy (and Why the Left-Wing Needs One, Too) -- tChapter 3 The Failure of Centrism and the Fall of the Democratic Party -- tChapter 4 Polls: The Circle of Lies -- tChapter 5 The Politics of Money: Campaign Financing and One Dollar, OneVote -- tChapter 6 The Myth of the Liberal Media: How the Press Attacks Progressives -- tChapter 7 The Globalization Wars: How the Left Won (and Lost) the "Battle in Seattle" -- tChapter 8 Pragmatic Progressives -- tChapter 9 Talking Tax Cuts: Lowering Taxes on the Poor -- tChapter 10 Making Crime a Progressive Issue -- tChapter 11 Winning the Culture Wars -- tChapter 12 Equality for Every Child: Reforming Education -- tChapter 13 Fighting the Union Label: Labor on the Left -- tChapter 14 The Race for Justice: Defending Affirmative Action -- tChapter 15 Universal Health Care -- tChapter 16 Greener Politics: Progressives and the Environment -- tChapter 17 Why We Need Welfare and How to Change It -- tChapter 18 Ending Corporate Welfare As We Know It -- tChapter 19 The Defense Industry: How to Protect America by Cutting the Military -- tChapter 20 Saving Social Security -- tChapter 21 The Future of Progressives: Generation Left -- tABOUT THE AUTHOR0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aIf we were to rely on what the pundits and politicians tell us, we would have to conclude that America is a deeply conservative nation. Americans, we hear constantly, detest government, demand lower taxes and the end of welfare, and favor the death penalty, prayer in school, and an absolute faith in the free market. And yet Americans believe deeply in progressive ideas. In fact, progressivism has long been a powerful force in the American psyche. Consider that a mere generation ago the struggle for environmentally sound policies, for women's rights, and for racial equality were fringe movements. Today, open opposition to these core ideals would be political suicide. Drawing on this wellspring of American progressivist tradition, John K. Wilson has penned an informal handbook for the pragmatic progressive. Wilson insists that the left must become more savvy in its rhetoric and stop preaching only to the converted. Progressives need to attack the tangible realities of the corporate welfare state, while explicitly acknowledging that "socialism is," as Wilson writes, "deader than Lenin." Rather than attacking a "right-wing conspiracy," Wilson argues that the left needs one, too. Tracing how well-funded conservative pressure groups have wielded their influence and transformed the national agenda, Wilson outlines a similar approach for the left. Along the way, he exposes the faultlines of our poll- and money-driven form of politics, explodes the myth of "the liberal media," and demands that the left explicitly change its image. Irreverent, practical, and urgently argued, How The Left Can Win Arguments and Influence People charts a way to translate progressive ideals into reality and reassert the core principles of the American left on the national stage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814795149.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814795149zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814795149/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA